<DOC><DOCNO> AP890320-0185 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2124EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-France-Corsica     03-20 0208</FIRST><SECOND>AM-France-Corsica,0215</SECOND><HEAD>Demonstrators battle police on strike-bound Corsica</HEAD><DATELINE>BASTIA, Corsica (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Travelers blocked by strikes at Corsica'sports and airports referred to themselves Monday as hostages, anddemonstrators battled police in the French island in theMediterranean.   Police threw tear gas grenades to disperse about 350 protestersthrowing stones and burning tires in front of this northern city'sadministrative offices. Officials said two policemen were injured.   A group of travelers unable to leave Corsica established a``committee of hostages'' and urged French officials to providemeans of evacuation ``to honor the elementary and constitutionalright of all citizens to freedom of movement.''   The island's ports and airports have been closed since the middleof last week in an escalation of the strike by public employees thatstarted five weeks ago.   French Premier Michel Rocard met in Paris with six Corsicanlegislators and said the government would organize discussions onreform programs with political, social and economic leaders ofCorsica.   He said success would depend a ``spirit of dialogue andresponsibility.''   Strikers are demanding what they call an insularity bonus tocompensate for high prices. Officials in Paris have not disputed thestrikers' claim that prices of basic goods are higher in Corsicathan in mainland France.</TEXT></DOC>